'''Adjunct professor''' ('''adjunct lecturer''' and '''adjunct instructor''', or '''adjunct faculty''' collectively) is a type of academic appointment in [[higher education]].
* In the [[Academic ranks in the United States|United States]], an adjunct is a non-[[Academic tenure|tenure-track]] faculty,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://education.cu-portland.edu/blog/teaching-careers/adjunct-professor/|title=What is an Adjunct Professor? Job Description & Salary|date=1 September 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jun/22/adjunct-professor-earn-less-than-pet-sitter|title=I am an adjunct professor who teaches five classes. I earn less than a pet-sitter - Lee Hall|first=Lee|last=Hall|date=22 June 2015|website=the Guardian}}</ref> though it can also be a scholar or teacher whose primary employer is not the school or department with which they have adjunct status. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/handbook/appointments-and-promotions/classification-of-ranks-and-titles|title=Classification of Ranks and Titles » Faculty Handbook - Boston University|website=www.bu.edu}}</ref> * In [[Academic ranks in Australia|Australia]], the term ''adjunct'' is reserved for academics and researchers from outside the university who have a close association with the university, e.g. through supervision of PhD students, recognised by an honorary title reflective of their rank and standing (Adjunct Lecturer, Senior Lecturer, Associate Professor or Professor). <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hr.uwa.edu.au/policies/policies/titles/adjunct-and-clinical-titles|title=Adjunct and clinical titles|first=The University of Western|last=Australia,|website=www.hr.uwa.edu.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ppl.app.uq.edu.au/content/5.20.15-honorary-and-adjunct-title-holders|title=Policies and Procedures Library - The University of Queensland, Australia|website=ppl.app.uq.edu.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jcu.edu.au/policy/hr-staff-development/adjunct-appointments|title=Adjunct Appointments|website=www.jcu.edu.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://policies.scu.edu.au/view.current.php?id=00027|title=SCU Policy Library - Adjunct, Visiting and Conjoint Appointments Policy|first=(TWEEK!)|last=www.tweek.com.au|website=policies.scu.edu.au}}</ref> * In Canada, adjunct professors are often nominated in recognition of active involvement with the appointing institution, while they are employed by government, industry, a profession or another institution <ref>https://www.unb.ca/gradstudies/_assets/pdfs/policyprocedure-adjunctprofessor.pdf</ref>. The position Course Lecturer, rather than adjunct, is used if the appointment is strictly to teach one or more courses, contrasting with US usage of the title for all instructors. * In [[Portugal]] the designation ''Professor Adjunto'' imply a stable full-time employment in a Polytechnic University. * In countries such as [[Academic ranks in Argentina|Argentina]] and [[Academic ranks in Brazil|Brazil]], a similar designation, ''Professor adjunto'', does imply stable full-time employment. * In parts of [[Academic ranks in Spain|Spain]], ''Profesor Adjunto'' is a non-tenured position. * In [[Academic ranks in Hungary|Hungary]], there exists a similar term ''Adjunktus'', as well as ''Adiunkt'' in [[List of academic ranks#Poland|Poland]]. * In [[Academic ranks in Bangladesh|Bangladesh]], private universities follow the title Adjunct Professor/Adjunct Associate Professor to imply non-tenure faculty members. * In [[Academic ranks in Thailand|Thailand]], Adjunct (Assistant/Associate) Professors are considered "non-regular officers". * In [[List of academic ranks#Pakistan|Pakistan]], Adjunct (Assistant/Associate) Professors are also considered as non-regular faculty members and usually posts are given to Pakistani overseas scientists under Faculty Development Program. * In [[Finland]], the Docents' Union of Finland and the Finnish Ministry of Education recommend the term Adjunct Professor in English as a translation of the title of [[Docent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.helsinki.fi/jarj/suomendosenttiliitto|title=Suomen Dosenttiliitto|website=www.helsinki.fi}}</ref> A docentship should be regarded as an educational title not connected with the employment pyramid as such, rather an assurance of the level of expertise, to enable the person to advance further in his/her academic career. The rank of a docent entitles scientists to be principal investigators, lead research groups and act as the supervisors of doctoral students.
